A better year for migrants?
DUBLIN – Two major lessons emerge from the migration crisis in the Mediterranean.
First, Europe and the international community are applying a cruelly unsuitable system for protecting the most vulnerable migrants.
Secondly, in the face of the ineffectiveness of this system, populist actors keep exploiting fears to gain political support, undermining liberal and tolerant societies whose construction required some 70 years of relentless effort.
This is why it is essential that this year a truly active effort be undertaken at both European and global levels.
In September next, the United Nations Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon will convene an extraordinary summit aimed at building a robust global system for the protection of the most vulnerable migrants and refugees.
We hope that States will be ready to commit concretely and sustainably.
This necessary commitment was sorely lacking throughout the year 2015.
In fact, the international community would have been able to limit the severity of last year's crisis if it had provided even the most modest support to the frontline countries – Turkey, Lebanon and Jordan – which together host no less than four million refugees.
With only about 10 billion euros, these countries would have been better able to house, feed and provide education for refugees, thus reducing the temptation of fleeing towards Europe.
This failure could cost Germany up to 21 billion € annually in the coming years.
However, the financial implications of the crisis are incomparable to its human and political cost.
Over a million people risked their lives last year by crossing the Mediterranean, enduring a exhausting journey through the Balkans afterwards.
Nearly 4,000 migrants lost their lives there, while many European countries turned their backs on the survivors by refusing to grant them asylum.
The most cynical political actors have mercilessly exploited citizens' fears, promoting an odious nationalist vision that either ignores or distorts the lived experiences of migrants.
In the United States, for example, not a single one of the 780,000 refugees settled since September 11, 2001, has been found guilty of terrorist activities.
At the same time, immigrants generally pay more taxes than they receive in social benefits.
Yet, extremist parties are dangerously flirting with gaining political power in some European countries, and are currently gaining support even within formerly liberal strongholds.
Anti-immigration parties are already in power in Hungary and Poland.
Their success is also leading traditional parties to promote hostile immigration policies themselves.
This situation has seriously undermined European cooperation.
The EU program aimed at dealing with the million refugees arriving on its shores has only managed to « relocate » 190.
Border controls in six countries belonging to the Schengen area have been reinstated, at least provisionally.
In the eyes of the rest of the world, the EU now appears chauvinist and incompetent.
Of course, resolving this crisis does not only concern Europe; responsibility cannot be defined solely by geographical proximity.
Regardless of everything, the EU is undoubtedly facing a threat to its own existence today, which it will only be able to overcome by firmly demonstrating the solidarity and international leadership it is capable of.
That is why it is up to the Member States to take the initiative by proposing solutions.
The most urgent priority is to establish legal and secure channels allowing refugees to reach Europe.
This does not mean asserting that every migrant in difficulty must be welcomed.
Nonetheless, it is incumbent upon the EU to be more systematically generous in determining the number of refugees to accept, and to employ orderly mechanisms aimed at facilitating their entry.
A system like this would allow protecting migrants while safeguarding Europe (by allowing for a full examination of applications).
Beyond a measure aimed at deterring asylum seekers from risking their lives by crossing the Mediterranean, such an approach would also project an image of solidarity towards frontline countries, which continue to host the majority of refugees.
An equally important aspect, this approach would encourage the rest of the international community to contribute to these efforts.
This leads us to the second priority of 2016: building a solid global system for the protection of vulnerable refugees and migrants.
This objective will first and foremost require that more countries accept to host refugees.
Ces dernières années, l'Agence des Nations Unies pour les réfugiés est seulement parvenue à réinstaller moins de 75 000 des quelque 20 millions de réfugiés annuels.
Plusieurs millions d'entre eux finissent dans une situation de migration prolongée, d'une durée moyenne estimée à 25 ans, prisonniers d'une sorte de purgatoire et incertains quant au jour d'un éventuel retour au pays.
En 2016, il est nécessaire que les pays développés consentent à accueillir chaque année un nombre cumulé proche du million de réfugiés, soit via leur réinstallation, soit en leur accordant un visa humanitaire, étudiant, professionnel ou autre.
Le Canada ayant affirmé qu'il accueillerait à lui seul 50 000 réfugiés syriens cette année, il s'agit d'un objectif clairement réalisable.
Dans le même temps, la communauté internationale devra appuyer l'intégration de réfugiés dans d'importants pays d'accueil tels que la Turquie, le Kenya, le Liban et la Jordanie.
As things stand currently, these countries only receive a fraction of the $3,000 to $5,000 annually needed for each refugee for housing, food, care, education, and vocational training during the first years of settlement.
And these figures do not take into account the necessary cost of constructing or upgrading infrastructure.
In Lebanon, for example, water supply systems are suffering from the pressure caused by the massive arrival of refugees.
In exchange for funding, these host countries could commit to fully integrating refugees into their schools, labor markets, and civic institutions.
But effective integration of migrants will only be possible if European and other countries rid themselves of their prejudices regarding migrants.
If these groups are still seen as a burden, or even as a threat to security, reactionary political forces will continue to gain ground, by depriving newcomers of opportunities and by turning fear into a self-fulfilling prophecy.
On the contrary, if host countries manage to integrate migrants enthusiastically, everyone will benefit – including these countries (notably through inflows of money).
Last month, in Paris, the international community proved that it was capable of subordinating its national interests to a broader global objective: the fight against climate change.
In 2016, it is necessary that a similar effort be directed towards building a better system for protecting migrants.
This is a matter of life or death for some 20 million refugees, for several million other vulnerable migrants – as well as a profound test of the civic health of democratic societies around the world.
